  "doi": "10.1126/sciimmunol.aav0860",
  "title": "High-throughput peptide-MHC complex generation and kinetic screenings of TCRs with peptide-receptive HLA-A*02:01 molecules.",
  "journal": "Science immunology",
  "year": 2019,
  "authors": "Moritz A, Anjanappa R, Wagner C, Bunk S, Hofmann M, Pszolla G, Saikia A, Garcia-Alai M, Meijers R, Rammensee HG, Springer S, Maurer D."
 },
 "executive_summary": "This study developed a disulfide-stabilized HLA-A*02:01 molecule that remains stable without peptide ligand, enabling efficient one-step loading with peptides of choice to generate pMHC complexes for structural and functional analysis. The researchers characterized wild-type and affinity-matured TCR binding to these engineered pMHCs using crystal structure determination and kinetic measurements, demonstrating that the engineered HLA variant behaves similarly to wild-type with respect to TCR recognition. They established a high-throughput platform to measure binding kinetics of bispecific TCRs (bsTCRs) against diverse pMHC libraries and showed that bsTCR affinity for pMHCs correlates with in vitro function, while generating a binding motif to predict off-target interactions in the human proteome. This platform is particularly relevant for cancer immunotherapy applications targeting tumor-associated neoantigens, as it enables rapid safety and efficacy screening of engineered TCR therapeutics against both intended and unintended pMHC targets.",
